        "excerpt": "I will lift up my eyes to the mountains; from where shall my help come? My help comes from the LORD, who made heaven and earth.",
        "body": "The psalm opens with a posture and a question. *I will lift up my eyes* — the Hebrew *nasa* (lift) is the same verb used elsewhere for lifting hands in prayer (Psalm 28:2), lifting a banner (Isaiah 13:2), lifting a burden (Psalm 55:22). To lift the eyes is to redirect attention, to take them off the road in front of you and look up. The pilgrim is somewhere on the ascent — perhaps days into a journey — and he lifts his head to scan the horizon. What does he see? *The mountains*.\n\nThe ambiguity of those mountains is the engine of the first verse. The Judean hill country was many things at once. It surrounded Jerusalem like a fortress (Psalm 125:2 — *as the mountains surround Jerusalem, so the LORD surrounds His people*). It could be the welcome sight of approaching the holy city. But the same hills also bore the *bamot*, the high places of Canaanite worship — fertility shrines to Baal, Asherah poles, smoke rising from local altars. Jeremiah 3:23 names the disillusionment directly: *truly in vain is salvation hoped for from the hills, and from the multitude of mountains*. To lift the eyes to the mountains is to face a choice. Is help here, in the topography itself, in the gods worshipped on these heights? Or somewhere else?\n\nThe pilgrim's question — *from where shall my help come?* — is therefore not rhetorical. It is genuinely diagnostic. He is asking himself, in front of the horizon, where he intends to look for rescue. And the second verse settles it with creational precision: *my help comes from the LORD, who made heaven and earth*. Notice what the answer does. It moves the source of help past the mountains to the One who *made* the mountains. It refuses to localize divine help in a place; it locates it in a Person. And the Person is identified by His most fundamental act — He is the Creator. The God who keeps you is the God who spoke the universe into being. His resources are not limited by the terrain you are crossing; the terrain itself is His handiwork.\n\nThe *ezer* (help) of verses 1 and 2 is covenantal vocabulary. The same word is used of Eve created as a helper suitable for Adam (Genesis 2:18), of the LORD as Israel's help in battle (Deuteronomy 33:7), of the priestly blessing in Numbers 6. This is not generic assistance; it is the active, faithful rescue of a stronger party for a weaker one in covenantal bond. The pilgrim is not asking for tips; he is appealing to a covenant relationship in which his Helper has obligated Himself.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nasa eynay* (\"I lift my eyes\") is the same idiom Jesus echoes in John 4:35 (*lift up your eyes and look on the fields*). *Ezri* (my help) shares its root with the name Ebenezer (1 Samuel 7:12 — *stone of help*). The phrase *oseh shamayim va'arets* (Maker of heaven and earth) appears repeatedly in the Psalter as a creedal formula (Psalms 115:15; 124:8; 134:3; 146:6) — it is shorthand for the entire confession of Genesis 1."
