        "number": 2,
        "title": "The Keeper who does not sleep",
        "range": "121:3-4",
        "excerpt": "He will not allow your foot to slip; He who keeps you will not slumber. Behold, He who keeps Israel will neither slumber nor sleep.",
        "body": "At verse 3 the voice changes. The first two verses were first-person — *I will lift, my help*. From verse 3 onward, the psalm speaks to the pilgrim in the second person — *your foot, your keeper, your soul*. Scholars debate whether this represents a priestly response in a liturgical setting, a fellow pilgrim's encouragement, or simply the psalmist turning to address his own soul. The pastoral point holds regardless: the pilgrim does not generate his own assurance in isolation. Another voice — covenantal, liturgical, communal — pronounces the keeping of the LORD over him. Faith is rarely a solo performance; it is received from one another in the covenant community.\n\nThe first specific promise is concrete and pedestrian: *He will not allow your foot to slip*. The Hebrew *mot* (slip, totter) is used elsewhere of the righteous never being moved (Psalm 15:5; 16:8; 55:22). On a literal Judean trail, this is the most immediate pilgrim concern — loose scree, an ankle turn, a fall down a slope. The Keeper's vigilance reaches into the smallest mechanics of the walk. He is not too cosmic to attend to your footing.\n\nVerses 3 and 4 then make the central claim of the psalm: *He who keeps you will not slumber. Behold, He who keeps Israel will neither slumber nor sleep*. Two verbs are stacked — *num* (to doze, nod off) and *yashen* (to sleep deeply) — to deny any inattention whatsoever. There is no momentary lapse and no extended unconsciousness. The doubling is theological polemic. The ancient Near Eastern gods slept. Elijah's mockery at Carmel is built precisely on this assumption — *cry aloud, for he is a god; either he is occupied, or he is gone aside, or he is on a journey, or perhaps he is asleep and must be awakened* (1 Kings 18:27). Baal slept. Marduk slept. The Egyptian pantheon required ritual awakening each morning. Yahweh does not.\n\nThe widening from \"He who keeps *you*\" (v. 3) to \"He who keeps *Israel*\" (v. 4) is structurally crucial. The same Keeper who attends to one pilgrim's foot is the Keeper of the entire covenant nation. There is no diminishment of attention as the scope expands. Divine providence is not a finite resource that has to be divided among recipients; the Keeper of Israel has full attention for every individual within Israel. The *hinneh* (\"behold\") at the head of verse 4 is the psalm's most emphatic attention-grabber — a verbal pointing finger directing the pilgrim to consider the magnitude of what has just been said.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shomer* (one who keeps) is the participial form of *shamar*, the psalm's dominant verb — appearing in vv. 3, 4, 5, 7 (×2), 8. *Lo yanum velo yishan* (will neither slumber nor sleep) is the emphatic doubled denial; the same verb pair appears together only here in the Hebrew Bible. The polemic against sleeping gods runs all the way through the canon — Psalm 44:23 (*Rouse Yourself! Why do You sleep, O Lord?*) is the lament that the LORD seems to be sleeping; Psalm 121 is the confession that He never actually does."
