        "number": 4,
        "title": "Keeping from all evil — body, soul, every transition",
        "range": "121:7-8",
        "excerpt": "The LORD will protect you from all evil; He will keep your soul. The LORD will guard your going out and your coming in from this time forth and forever.",
        "body": "The psalm's final two verses make the keeping comprehensive across three axes: scope of threat (*from all evil*), depth of self (*your soul / nephesh*), and span of life (*your going out and coming in, from this time forth and forever*). The repetition of *shamar* hits its rhetorical climax here — three times in two verses (*will protect, will keep, will guard*), pressing the verb's dominance to its peak before the psalm closes.\n\n*The LORD will protect you from all evil* (*mikol-ra*) is the broadest possible scope-claim. *Ra* in Hebrew covers everything from physical calamity to moral evil to disaster of every kind — Genesis 2:9 (the tree of knowledge of good and *evil*), Job 2:10 (*shall we accept good from God and not adversity?*), Deuteronomy 30:15 (*life and good, death and evil*). The psalm's claim is not that the believer will be exempt from encountering *ra* — Scripture is everywhere clear that the righteous suffer (Psalm 34:19; John 16:33) — but that *ra* will not have the last word over the kept one. The Keeper protects *from* it in the sense of preserving His pilgrim through it.\n\nThe pairing with *He will keep your soul* (*nephesh*) clarifies. *Nephesh* is not the disembodied 'soul' of later Platonism; it is the whole living self — life, breath, person, identity. To keep the *nephesh* is to preserve the whole personhood. Romans 8:35-39 makes the New Testament version of the same claim: tribulation, distress, persecution, famine, nakedness, danger, sword — none of it separates the kept one from the love of God in Christ. External *ra* may strike; the *nephesh* remains kept.\n\nThe final verse closes with two merisms layered together. *Going out and coming in* (*tzetcha uvoeka*) is standard Hebrew idiom for the totality of life and activity — Deuteronomy 28:6 promises blessing on the going out and coming in of the obedient; 1 Kings 3:7 has Solomon confess he does not know how to *go out or come in* as Israel's king; Numbers 27:17 describes a leader as one who *goes out before them and comes in before them*. Every departure, every return, every transition between phases of life — under the same keeping. Then *from this time forth and forever* (*me'attah ve'ad-olam*) extends the keeping into eternity. The psalm closes with the largest possible temporal frame; the pilgrim's journey on a Judean road becomes the believer's journey through life and beyond.\n\nFor Christian readers, the psalm's climax finds its richest fulfillment in Jesus's high-priestly prayer: *Holy Father, keep them in Your name, the name which You have given Me, that they may be one even as We are. While I was with them, I was keeping them in Your name which You have given Me; and I guarded them and not one of them perished* (John 17:11-12). The same verb-cluster — *keep, guard* — and the same theological structure: the Father keeps, the Son keeps, the kept ones do not perish. Jude 24 caps the canonical trajectory: *now to Him who is able to keep you from stumbling, and to make you stand in the presence of His glory blameless with great joy*. The foot that the LORD will not allow to slip in Psalm 121:3 is the same foot Jude promises will be kept from final stumbling at the consummation.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tzetcha uvoeka* (your going out and your coming in) is a comprehensive merism — Deuteronomy 28:6, 31:2; 1 Samuel 29:6; 2 Samuel 3:25. *Me'attah ve'ad-olam* (from this time forth and forever) appears as a closing benediction in Psalms 113:2; 115:18; 125:2; 131:3 — a Psalter-wide formula for unending divine commitment. The progression from *foot* (v. 3) to *nephesh* (v. 7) to *all going out and coming in forever* (v. 8) is the psalm's structural climax — the keeping starts at the ankles and ends at eternity."
